data.content:
Here's the audit. This class has **systemic problems** — 3 Critical, 2 High, 1 Medium, 3 Low findings. Several tests will pass regardless of whether the code under test is correct, which directly explains your prod incident.

---

## 🔴 Critical — False confidence (fix immediately)

### 1. `GetUser_NonExistentId_ReturnsNull` — No assertion
The test retrieves a user but never asserts anything. It always passes.
```csharp
// BEFORE
var user = repo.GetById(999);
// should be null

// AFTER
var user = repo.GetById(999);
Assert.IsNull(user);
```

### 2. `AddUser_DuplicateId_ThrowsException` — Swallowed exception
The `try/catch` silently passes whether or not an exception is thrown. If the duplicate-check regresses, this test still passes.
```csharp
// BEFORE
try {
    repo.Add(new User(1, "Bob"));
} catch (Exception) { return; }

// AFTER
Assert.ThrowsException<InvalidOperationException>(
    () => repo.Add(new User(1, "Bob")));
```

### 3. `DeleteUser_RemovesFromRepository` — Always-true assertion
`Assert.AreEqual(repo.Count, repo.Count)` compares the value to **itself**. This can never fail.
```csharp
// BEFORE
Assert.AreEqual(repo.Count, repo.Count);

// AFTER
Assert.AreEqual(0, repo.Count);
```

---

## 🟠 High — Will cause pain

### 4. `AddUser_NullUser_ThrowsArgumentNullException` — Broad exception type
Asserts `Exception` but the method name promises `ArgumentNullException`. Any crash (including `NullReferenceException` from a missing guard) would pass this test.
```csharp
// BEFORE
Assert.ThrowsException<Exception>(() => repo.Add(null!));

// AFTER
Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(() => repo.Add(null!));
```

### 5. `UpdateUser_ChangesName` — Weak negative assertion
`user.Name != "Alice"` only checks the old name is gone, not that the new name is correct. If `Update` set the name to garbage, this still passes.
```csharp
// BEFORE
Assert.IsTrue(user.Name != "Alice");

// AFTER
Assert.AreEqual("Alicia", user.Name);
```

---

## 🟡 Medium / Low

| Severity | Location | Issue | Fix |
|----------|----------|-------|-----|
| Medium | `GetUser_ExistingId_ReturnsUser` | Only asserts `IsNotNull`, never checks Id/Name — wrong user would pass | Add `Assert.AreEqual("Alice", user.Name)` |
| Low | Class field `_client` | Unused static `HttpClient` (also `IDisposable`) | Remove it |
| Low | `SearchUsers_ByPartialName` | `Console.WriteLine` leftover | Remove it |
| Low | `SearchUsers_ByPartialName` | `Assert.IsTrue(x == 2)` gives poor failure diagnostics | Use `Assert.AreEqual(2, results.Count)` |

---

## ✅ Positive observations
- **`GetAllUsers_ReturnsCorrectCount`** is well-written: checks count *and* verifies each element.
- Naming convention is consistent (`Method_Scenario_Expected`).
- Each test creates its own `UserRepository` — good isolation.

---

**Priority**: Fix the 3 Critical items first — they are the tests that currently provide zero protection against regressions.
